This article is a Presidential Memorandum from January 15, 2015, discussing the need to modernize federal leave policies for childbirth, adoption, and foster care in order to recruit and retain talent and improve productivity. The memo emphasizes the importance of supporting parents in the workplace and highlights the benefits of paid maternity and paternity leave. It acknowledges that the United States lags behind other countries in providing paid parental leave for its federal workforce. The memorandum directs executive departments and agencies to utilize workplace flexibilities and work-life programs to promote recruitment, retention, employee engagement, and workforce productivity. It also outlines specific actions to be taken, such as offering advanced sick and annual leave, providing emergency backup dependent care services, and updating leave policies. The Office of Personnel Management (OPM) is tasked with issuing guidance and implementing the necessary changes. The memorandum concludes with general provisions regarding the implementation of the memo and its limitations.